=09Changing course :: As the new CEO of Harley-Davidson, Zeitz was charg=
ed with transforming the legendary brand for the future. While Harley-David=
son=E2=80=99s iconic Easy Rider-influenced brand built a loyal customer bas=
e, many customers are aging and hesitant to see the company evolve. Meanwhi=
le, there=E2=80=99s a large group of potential customers who aren=E2=80=
=99t attracted to the traditional Harley brand, as they have different aspi=
rations from the core customers. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s the dichotomy we n=
eed to address with a specific strategy that still delivers what the core w=
ants but also reaches out with new and exciting products, language and mess=
aging that=E2=80=99s quite different.=E2=80=9D One part of this strategy is=
 the electric motorcycle, which reaches out to new customers by providing =
=E2=80=9Cthe Harley look and feel=E2=80=9D but in a modern, sustainable way=
.

=09Starting from scratch :: Although the road to building the electr=
ic motorcycle could rely on Harley-Davidson=E2=80=99s brand name and legacy=
, said Zeitz, =E2=80=9CEverything else is starting from scratch. So I look =
at this venture as a startup, and we need to structure it that way.=
=E2=80=9D This creates challenges, as different metrics are needed for the =
nascent electric part of the business and the traditional part of the busin=
ess, which is driving revenue. =E2=80=9CYou don=E2=80=99t want to cannibali=
ze your traditional business by taking your eye off the ball, but you know =
to compete in electric, you need a completely different mindset, mentality =
and focus.=E2=80=9D The motorcycle industry is behind the auto industry in =
embracing electricity, but the market will move in that direction. =
=E2=80=9CThis is a long-term play. We have to think in decades rather than =
years.=E2=80=9D=20

=09Welcome the criticism :: While some traditionalist=
s in the motorcycle space might denounce the idea of an electric motorcycle=
, Zeitz observed that this criticism comes with the territory of innovation=
. Any truly innovative product=E2=80=94from the first cell phones to the Te=
sla=E2=80=94inevitably faces a host of criticism at first. =E2=80=9CIf you =
want to lead and innovate, from my perspective, the more resistance you get=
, the bigger you are in terms of innovation,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CYou=
 just have to keep at it, and do the right things.=E2=80=9D=20

=09Drivin=
g change through business :: =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve learned in my career tha=
