 such as sustainability and digital acceleration. On sustainability, she sa=
id, =E2=80=9CMy company is squarely the most sustainable way to get dressed=
.=E2=80=9D Apparel has been one of the slowest industries to embrace digita=
l commerce, but 99% of Rent the Runway=E2=80=99s sales already happen onlin=
e. Seeing these trends, Hyman realized her company was positioned to be eve=
n bigger coming out of the crisis.

=09The next trend :: The fashion in=
dustry=E2=80=99s biggest upcoming trend is the transition toward becoming t=
ruly sustainable. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s part of the thesis we have that t=
he circular economy is going to be an even bigger part of the fashion indus=
try going forward.=E2=80=9D A small but growing part of Rent the Runway=
=E2=80=99s business was selling second-hand clothes, and Hyman decided to e=
xpand the business model and position the company as the platform for the c=
ircular economy in fashion=E2=80=94as the place where =E2=80=9Ca customer c=
an come and decide, with every unit of inventory, whether you want to rent =
it, subscribe to it or purchase it.=E2=80=9D While many companies jettisone=
d ancillary businesses during the pandemic, Rent the Runway did the opposit=
e by =E2=80=9Cwidening the aperture of the value proposition.=E2=80=9D She =
said, =E2=80=9CEven though the short term is going to suck, let=E2=80=99s m=
ake sure that we prioritize to come out of this to more strongly capture a =
much larger opportunity.=E2=80=9D

=09Mapping the mood :: Rent the Runw=
ay=E2=80=99s analytics team refined customer data by geography throughout t=
