=09Seeing like a rock-onomist :: The pandemic has=
 accelerated trends and changed the behaviors of consumers and businesses a=
like. To see around corners, ask the question: When the pandemic ends, how =
might these before and after behaviors coexist? For example, in the music i=
ndustry, during COVID-19, the streaming business has grown, but the live mu=
sic business imploded. Artists have successfully embraced technology to hos=
t livestreamed performances. Live music will come back after COVID-19, but =
livestreaming won=E2=80=99t simply go away. Thus, Page is thinking about ho=
w these will coexist and how they might complement rather than compete with=
 each other. =E2=80=9COften, a traditional business mindset will see things=
 as a threat. But a rock-onomist=E2=80=99s job is to see that as an opportu=
nity.=E2=80=9D

=09Be misunderstood :: While discussing having a long-t=
erm mindset for innovation, Page recalled hearing Jeff Bezos say to =
=E2=80=9Cbe prepared to be misunderstood for generations.=E2=80=9D One of A=
mazon=E2=80=99s earliest acquisitions was IMDb, and the fruits of that are =
just now appearing. If you pause a movie on Amazon Prime Video, you can see=
 the names of the actors in the scene and information about the song playin=
g in the background. =E2=80=9CThat is an example of somebody thinking long =
term to say, =E2=80=98How do you enrich the experience of watching a movie =
on their sofa in a way you can=E2=80=99t do in the cinema?=E2=80=99=
=E2=80=9D Page challenged members, asking: =E2=80=9CWhat would be your =
