;" width=3D"140"></a></em></p>

<ul>
=09<li><strong>Changing course :=
:</strong>&nbsp;As the new CEO of Harley-Davidson, Zeitz was charged with t=
ransforming the legendary brand for the future. While Harley-Davidson=
=E2=80=99s iconic&nbsp;<em>Easy Rider</em>-influenced brand built a loyal c=
ustomer base, many customers are aging and hesitant to see the company evol=
ve. Meanwhile, there=E2=80=99s a large group of potential customers who are=
n=E2=80=99t attracted to the traditional Harley brand, as they have differe=
nt aspirations from the core customers. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s the dichoto=
my we need to address with a specific strategy that still delivers what the=
 core wants but also reaches out with new and exciting products, language a=
nd messaging that=E2=80=99s quite different.=E2=80=9D One part of this stra=
tegy is the electric motorcycle, which reaches out to new customers by prov=
iding =E2=80=9Cthe Harley look and feel=E2=80=9D but in a modern, sustainab=
le way.</li>
=09<li><strong>Starting from scratch ::</strong>&nbsp;Althou=
gh the road to building the electric motorcycle could rely on Harley-Davids=
on=E2=80=99s brand name and legacy, said Zeitz, =E2=80=9CEverything else is=
 starting from scratch. So I look at this venture as a startup, and we need=
 to structure it that way.=E2=80=9D This creates challenges, as different m=
etrics are needed for the nascent electric part of the business and the tra=
ditional part of the business, which is driving revenue. =E2=80=9CYou don=
=E2=80=99t want to cannibalize your traditional business by taking your eye=
 off the ball, but you know to compete in electric, you need a completely d=
ifferent mindset, mentality and focus.=E2=80=9D The motorcycle industry is =
behind the auto industry in embracing electricity, but the market will move=
 in that direction. =E2=80=9CThis is a long-term play. We have to think in =
decades rather than years.=E2=80=9D&nbsp;</li>
=09<li><strong>Welcome the=
 criticism ::&nbsp;</strong>While some traditionalists in the motorcycle sp=
ace might denounce the idea of an electric motorcycle, Zeitz observed that =
this criticism comes with the territory of innovation. Any truly innovative=
 product=E2=80=94from the first cell phones to the Tesla=E2=80=94inevitably=
 faces a host of criticism at first. =E2=80=9CIf you want to lead and innov=
ate, from my perspective, the more resistance you get, the bigger you are i=
n terms of innovation,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CYou just have to keep at =
it, and do the right things.=E2=80=9D&nbsp;</li>
=09<li><strong>Driving c=
hange through business ::</strong>&nbsp;=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve learned in my=
 career that business, while it does a lot of good, does a lot of harm, too=
, from a social and environmental point of view,=E2=80=9D said Zeitz. But, =
business has a huge opportunity to solve the major problems plaguing the wo=
rld. Zeitz co-founded The B Team with Sir Richard Branson to activate the t=
ransformative power of business in solving global problems and to reframe s=
ustainability as an opportunity rather than a responsibility. The B Team=
=E2=80=99s recent work focuses on promoting an inclusive stakeholder approa=
ch, which Zeitz is implementing at Harley-Davidson, as he did at Puma. Whil=
e he acknowledged that large-scale transformation is a long-term process, h=
e said: =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m a realistic optimist. =E2=80=A6 We=E2=80=99re =
starting to realize what the problems are and starting to find solutions. I=
 remain optimistic that we
can solve the issues we=E2=80=99re facing.=
=E2=80=9D&nbsp;</li>
</ul>
