<ul>
=09<li><strong>A fashion emergency ::</strong>=
&nbsp;Before COVID-19, Rent the Runway was on a 10-year =E2=80=9Crocket-shi=
p growth path,=E2=80=9D building the =E2=80=9Ccloset in the cloud=E2=80=
=9D for its many customers. As the virus disrupted China=E2=80=99s fashion =
supply chains in January, the company quickly sought to mitigate inventory =
shortages. By mid-March, inventory had arrived, but shelter-in-place orders=
 were enacted, decimating Rent the Runway=E2=80=99s demand. Faced with no r=
evenue and many fixed costs, Hyman had to act swiftly to save the company s=
he founded, slashing costs and making difficult people decisions. =E2=80=
=9CIt was a traumatic eight-day experience,=E2=80=9D she said. =E2=80=9CI h=
ad to do everything possible to not only save the business but to save the =
passion and the work of the thousands of people who=E2=80=99ve partnered wi=
th me over the last decade to build this industry-leading company.=E2=80=
=9D</li>
=09<li><strong>Alter your view ::</strong>&nbsp;In the past, emp=
loyees came to work at the fast-growing company expecting to manage lots of=
 successful projects and to rise in their roles and responsibilities quickl=
y. When the business changed almost overnight, Hyman had to reframe how emp=
loyees saw their jobs in order to prevent mass attrition and motivate them =
through the crisis. =E2=80=9CI had to convince people that their jobs were =
to learn how to connect emotionally with folks on their team, how to inspir=
e people around them, how to ruthlessly prioritize what they=E2=80=99re wor=
king on, how to figure out how to do more with less.=E2=80=9D She champione=
d the idea of resilient leadership and emphasized that every employee is re=
sponsible for it.&nbsp;</li>
=09<li><strong>Address the existential quest=
ions ::&nbsp;</strong>Faced with an existential crisis, Hyman and her team =
asked themselves two essential questions that guided their strategy during =
COVID-19 and provided an outlook for a post-pandemic future:&nbsp;
=09<ol=
>
=09=09<li><strong>Will your business still be relevant after COVID-19?&=
nbsp;</strong>The whole world is suffering from the same crisis at the same=
 time, and this is fundamentally changing our values, how we live and how w=
e work. =E2=80=9CThese trends are not necessarily going away.=E2=80=9D Afte=
r pondering the question, Hyman determined that Rent the Runway still had a=
 place in a post-COVID-19 world. =E2=80=9CYes, I think creating a sharing e=
conomy in a closet in the cloud is still relevant.=E2=80=9D</li>
=09=09<l=
i><strong>Coming out of COVID-19, will your business be more relevant or le=
ss relevant than it was before?&nbsp;</strong>Consider the shifting values =
and trends during the pandemic, such as sustainability and digital accelera=
tion. On sustainability, she said, =E2=80=9CMy company is squarely the most=
 sustainable way to get dressed.=E2=80=9D Apparel has been one of the slowe=
st industries to embrace digital commerce, but 99% of Rent the Runway=
=E2=80=99s sales already happen online. Seeing these trends, Hyman realized=
 her company was positioned to be even bigger coming out of the crisis.</li=
>
=09</ol>
=09</li>
=09<li><strong>The next trend ::&nbsp;</strong>Th=
e fashion industry=E2=80=99s biggest upcoming trend is the transition towar=
d becoming truly sustainable. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s part of the thesis we=
 have that the circular economy is going to be an even bigger part of the f=
ashion industry going forward.=E2=80=9D A small but growing part of Rent th=
e Runway=E2=80=99s business was selling second-hand clothes, and Hyman deci=
ded to expand the business model and position the company as the platform f=
or the circular economy in fashion=E2=80=94as the place where =E2=80=9Ca cu=
stomer can come and decide, with every unit of inventory, whether you want =
to rent it, subscribe to it or purchase it.=E2=80=9D While many companies j=
ettisoned ancillary businesses during the pandemic, Rent the Runway did the=
 opposite by =E2=80=9Cwidening the aperture of the value proposition.=
=E2=80=9D She said, =E2=80=9CEven though the short term is going to suck, l=
et=E2=80=99s make sure that we
prioritize to come out of this to more str=
ongly capture a much larger opportunity.=E2=80=9D</li>
=09<li><strong>Map=
ping the mood ::</strong>&nbsp;Rent the Runway=E2=80=99s analytics team ref=
ined customer data by geography throughout the pandemic, revealing signific=
ant regional differences in customers=E2=80=99 outlook. In states like Texa=
s, Georgia and Florida, Rent the Runway=E2=80=99s business is accelerating,=
 and almost 75% of customers in those markets have returned despite high CO=
VID-19 case numbers. The opposite effect is happening in states like Califo=
rnia and New York. =E2=80=9CEven though the rates of COVID are much lower i=
n New York right now than in Georgia,=E2=80=9D she said, =E2=80=9Cthe psych=
ology of the consumer is fundamentally different in New York, and she=
=E2=80=99s not yet ready to resume her life as normal.=E2=80=9D&nbsp;</li>=

