li><strong>Listen out for signals ::&nbsp;</strong>Be wary about relying to=
o heavily on data when you=E2=80=99re trying to see ahead and detect future=
 risks and opportunities. =E2=80=9CRemember that all data comes from the sa=
me place: the past,=E2=80=9D said Page. Be open to exploring new signals=
=E2=80=94even seemingly unusual ones=E2=80=94in the present that may shed l=
ight on the future. For example, in 2018, the Bank of England=E2=80=99s chi=
ef economist wanted to use Spotify=E2=80=99s data to help predict the next =
recession. He wanted to understand what was happening in the economy at tha=
t very moment, and he wanted to look for signals of anxiety in Spotify=
=E2=80=99s listener data. =E2=80=9CAnxiety could have a much bigger impact =
on how the economy responds to a crisis than last quarter=E2=80=99s manufac=
turing output data.=E2=80=9D</li>
=09<li><strong>Data science needs commo=
n sense ::</strong>&nbsp;Page warned that data strategies must be supplemen=
ted by common sense, as data dashboards tend to overlook common-sense obser=
vations. When Spotify launched its Discover Weekly playlists, Page worked c=
losely with the data team, but then he met with the customer support team. =
From that, he learned that customers would call to ask why&nbsp;<em>Frozen<=
/em>&nbsp;songs were appearing on their Discover Weekly playlists, and that=
 the support team would realize these customers had children and would succ=
essfully sell them a family plan. =E2=80=9CThe customization of Discover We=
ekly =E2=80=A6 was driving the commerce of the family plan,=E2=80=9D he sai=
d, but the =E2=80=9Ctunnel vision=E2=80=9D of the data scientists didn=
=E2=80=99t see this connection. Only by listening to the customer and apply=
ing common sense could anyone uncover that opportunity. =E2=80=9CA chief da=
ta
scientist is employed to study data, but you need to counterbalance th=
at with the people who produce that data. That=E2=80=99s the link I encoura=
ge you to close.=E2=80=9D&nbsp;</li>
=09<li><strong>The war for attention=
 ::</strong>&nbsp;Every platform is fighting a war for users=E2=80=99 atten=
tion. =E2=80=9CIf Netflix gets me to binge-watch three times 10 episodes of=
&nbsp;<em>Narcos</em>, which I did,=E2=80=9D he said, =E2=80=9Cthat=
=E2=80=99s 30 hours that music doesn=E2=80=99t see, that Facebook or Instag=
ram doesn=E2=80=99t see.=E2=80=9D Netflix has won the attention war for 30 =
hours. Page believes that companies must start by gaining attention and the=
n move on from there. =E2=80=9CIf I win your attention, I can win lots of o=
ther things.=E2=80=9D While people are paying for and listening to music, m=
usic is =E2=80=9Cjust wallpaper,=E2=80=9D so Spotify needed a new way to ca=
pture users=E2=80=99 attention. Listening to a podcast requires paying more=
 attention than listening to music does, so Spotify=E2=80=99s move into the=
 podcast business is an effort to compete in the attention war. =E2=80=
=9CMeans to an end is how I approach iteration. And podcasts were a
means=
 to an attention-winning end.=E2=80=9D</li>
=09<li><strong>Seeing like a =
rock-onomist ::</strong>&nbsp;The pandemic has accelerated trends and chang=
ed the behaviors of consumers and businesses alike. To see around corners, =
ask the question: When the pandemic ends, how might these before and after =
behaviors coexist? For example, in the music industry, during COVID-19, the=
 streaming business has grown, but the live music business imploded. Artist=
s have successfully embraced technology to host livestreamed performances. =
Live music will come back after COVID-19, but livestreaming won=E2=80=99t s=
imply go away. Thus, Page is thinking about how these will coexist and how =
they might complement rather than compete with each other. =E2=80=9COften, =
a traditional business mindset will see things as a threat. But a rock-onom=
ist=E2=80=99s job is to see that as an opportunity.=E2=80=9D</li>
=09<li>=
<strong>Be misunderstood ::&nbsp;</strong>While discussing having a long-te=
rm mindset for innovation, Page recalled hearing Jeff Bezos say to =
=E2=80=9Cbe prepared to be misunderstood for generations.=E2=80=9D One of A=
mazon=E2=80=99s earliest acquisitions was IMDb, and the fruits of that are =
just now appearing. If you pause a movie on Amazon Prime Video, you can see=
 the names of the actors in the scene and information about the song playin=
g in the background. =E2=80=9CThat is an example of somebody thinking long =
term to say, =E2=80=98How do you enrich the experience of watching a movie =
on their sofa in a way you can=E2=80=99t do in the cinema?=E2=80=99=
=E2=80=9D Page challenged members, asking: =E2=80=9CWhat would be your =
=E2=80=98IMDb acquisition=E2=80=99=E2=80=94where you really have to think d=
ecades ahead before you see the fruits of it or before you can yield that i=
nvestment back?=E2=80=9D</li>
